public interface ObjectLike

An opaque interface resembling JavaScript objects.

This interface must be implemented in JS Simulation Libraries.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
Initializer.var(), Js.object(), Js.object(Object), JsObject.JsObject(), JsGlobal.Object.create()
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

hasOwnProperty

java.lang.Boolean hasOwnProperty(java.lang.Object propname)

Checks whether the current object instance has a locally defined (non-inherited) property with a specified name.

JavaScript objects may have properties of their own, and they may also inherit properties from their prototype object. This method provides a way to distinguish between inherited properties and non-inherited local properties

Parameters:
propname - A string that contains the name of a property of the current object instance.
Returns:
true if the current object instance has a non-inherited property with the name specified by propname; false if the object does not have a property with the specified name or if it inherits that property from its prototype object.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

isPrototypeOf

java.lang.Boolean isPrototypeOf(java.lang.Object other)

Checks whether the current object instance is the prototype object of a specified object.

This method provides a way to determine if one Object object is the prototype of another

In JavaScript, Object objects inherit properties from their prototype object. The prototype of an Object object is referred to by the prototype property of the constructor function that creates and initializes the object.

Not that, in JS Embed Simulation mode, this method always returns false on a simulated object instance of ObjectLike, unless the instance is converted to a JavaScript object by var().

Parameters:
other - Any object.
Returns:
true if the current object instance is the prototype of other; false if other is not an Object object or if the current object instance is not the prototype of other.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsObject.Members.constructor, JsClass.prototype
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

propertyIsEnumerable

java.lang.Boolean propertyIsEnumerable(java.lang.Object propname)

Checks whether a named property exists and would be enumerable in JavaScript.

Parameters:
propname - A string that contains the name of a property of the current object instance.
Returns:
true if the current object instance has a non-inherited property with the name specified by propname and if that property is enumerable, which means that it would be enumerated by a for/in loop on the current object instance in JavaScript.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

var

JsObject var()

Simply returns the object of the current instance.

This method is useful for JS Simulation to implement opaque types.

If the current instance is a Java simulated object and the method runs in JS Embed Simulation mode, the invocation creates and returns a JavaScript Object object as a runtime copy of the current instance.

Returns:
The object of the current instance.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must ignore the interface invocation of this method, that is, replacing it with its current instance.
